Problem 9.6

Part (a)

corr1 <- Olympics2012 %>% 
  summarize(correlation = cor(Height, Weight))
corr1
  correlation
1   0.5083801

Part (b)

Note: For “What do you observe?”, comment on linearity, direction of trend, and outliers.

ggplot(Olympics2012, aes(x = Height, y = Weight)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_jitter() +
  labs(title = "Weight vs. Height of Selected 2012 Olympic Athletes",
       x = "Height (inches)",
       y = "Weight (pounds)",
       caption = "source: MSRR Olympics2012 dataset")

ANSWER: There seems to be a positive linear trend where weight increases with height. There are some outliers, people who are unusually heavy compared to others of the same height.

Part (c)

Hint: Use filter() with Weight to remove the outliers.

corr2 <- Olympics2012 %>% 
  filter(Weight < 250) %>% 
  summarize(correlation = cor(Height, Weight))
corr_diff <- corr2 - corr1
corr_diff
  correlation
1   0.2983159

ANSWER: The correlation increased by about 0.298 when the outliers were removed, so they appear to haver been influential. The relationship is more strongly linear without those points.

Reminder: You can embed the value of a calculated object like corr_diff in the text of your answer rather than typing it by hand. This enhances reprodicibility. See the Basic R Markdown Cheat Sheet > 5. Embed Code > inline code.

# extra--note you can filter a dataset inside ggplot2
# the trend looks a little less straight in this plot
ggplot(filter(Olympics2012, Weight < 250), aes(x = Height, y = Weight)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_jitter() +
  labs(title = "Weight vs. Height of Selected 2012 Olympic Athletes",
       subtitle = "note: bivariate outliers with weights over 250 pounds removed",
       x = "Height (inches)",
       y = "Weight (pounds)",
       caption = "source: MSRR Olympics2012 dataset")

Problem 9.8

Part (a)

# coloring by team is extra, to help visualize correlation difference
ggplot(RangersTwins2016, aes(x = BA, y = RBI, color = Team)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_jitter() +
  labs(title = "RBI versus BA for Texas Rangers and Minnesota Twins in 2016",
       x = "batting average (BA)",
       y = "runs batted in (RBI)",
       caption = "source: MSRR RangersTwins2016")

RangersTwins2016 %>% 
  summarize(correlation = cor(BA, RBI))
  correlation
1   0.4686685

Part (b)

RangersTwins2016 %>% 
  group_by(Team) %>% 
  summarize(correlation = cor(BA, RBI))
# A tibble: 2 x 2
  Team    correlation
  <fct>         <dbl>
1 Rangers       0.683
2 Twins         0.156

ANSWER: The Rangers alone had a stronger correlation than the combined teams, while the Twins had a weaker correlation. (But, when looking at the plot, neither relationship seems strictly linear.)

Problem 9.9

Part (a)

Note: Also make a scatterplot of field goal percentage versus offensive rebounds.

ggplot(NBA1617, aes(x = OffReb, y = PercFG)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "Field Goal Percentage vs. Offensive Rebounds",
       subtitle = "data for selected NBA players during the 2016-2017 season",
       x = "number of offensive rebounds",
       y = "field goal percentage",
       caption = "source: MSRR NBA1617 dataset")

NBA1617 %>% 
  summarize(correlation = cor(PercFG, OffReb))
  correlation
1   0.4898055

Part (b)

team_means <- NBA1617 %>% 
  group_by(Team) %>% 
  summarize(xbar_PercFG = mean(PercFG),
            xbar_OffReb = mean(OffReb))
team_means
# A tibble: 4 x 3
  Team        xbar_PercFG xbar_OffReb
  <fct>             <dbl>       <dbl>
1 Brooklyn           43.8        37.5
2 Charlotte          46.2        44.7
3 Cleveland          44.8        44.6
4 San Antonio        47.0        51.3

Part (c)

ggplot(team_means, aes(x = xbar_OffReb, y = xbar_PercFG)) +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_label(aes(label = Team), 
             hjust = c(0, 1, 0, 1), 
             nudge_x = c(.1, -.1, .1, -.1), 
             vjust = c(0, 0, 1, 1), 
             nudge_y = c(.1, .1, -.1, -.1)) +
  labs(title = "Field Goal Percentage vs. Offensive Rebounds",
       subtitle = "mean data for four NBA teams during the 2016-2017 season",
       x = "mean number of offensive rebounds",
       y = "mean field goal percentage",
       caption = "source: MSRR NBA1617 dataset")

team_means %>% 
  summarize(correlation = cor(xbar_PercFG, xbar_OffReb))
# A tibble: 1 x 1
  correlation
        <dbl>
1       0.911

ANSWER: The correlation is stronger for the averaged team data than the individual players.

Problem 9.16

Part (a)

ggplot(Beerwings, aes(x = Hotwings, y = Beer)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "Beer Consumption vs. Hot Wing Consumption",
       x = "number of hot wings",
       y = "ounces of beer",
       caption = "source: MSRR Hotwings dataset")

Beerwings %>% 
  summarize(correlation = cor(Beer, Hotwings))
  correlation
1   0.7841224

Part (b)

wing_model <- lm(Beer ~ Hotwings, data = Beerwings)
wing_model

Call:
lm(formula = Beer ~ Hotwings, data = Beerwings)

Coefficients:
(Intercept)     Hotwings  
      3.040        1.941

INTERPRETATION: The equation of the least-squares regression line is \(\hat{y}\) = 3.04 + 1.941(\(x\)). For each additional hot wing eaten, a person consumes an additional 1.94 ounces of beer (on average).

Part (c)

wing_summaries <- get_regression_summaries(wing_model)
wing_summaries$r_squared
[1] 0.615

INTERPRETATION: About 61.5% of the variability in ounces of beer consumed is explained by number of hot wings eaten.

Part (d) ADDED Perform a residual analysis like MD 6.1.4 and comment on the appropriateness of a straight-line model.

wing_points <- get_regression_points(wing_model)

ggplot(wing_points, aes(x = residual)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 6)

ggplot(wing_points, aes(x = Hotwings, y = residual)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0) +
  labs(x = "number of hot wings (x)")

ANSWER: The histogram is very slightly left skewed and the scatterplot of residuals versus x seems to show some non-random
